d:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["The grim arithmetic is confirmed: at least 57 nations hold live antipersonnel mines, which killed 1,945 people and injured 4,325 in 2024 alone, 90% of them civilians. Demining crews removed over 105,640 mines that same year, a dangerous, painstaking process. The promise of combining drones and AI to make this faster and safer is compelling. According to available information, the technique involves drones equipped with multispectral sensors and ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S092188902300123X","children":"machine learning models"}]," surveying large areas to flag anomalies. This could theoretically keep humans at a safer distance during initial scans. Early signals suggest this can accelerate the mapping phase, a crucial first step documented by groups like ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.halotrust.org/","children":"The HALO Trust"}],".\nThe demo footage is convincing: a drone flies a pre-programmed grid, its AI highlighting potential threats on a clean map. But the real question isn't about the algorithm's accuracy in a controlled test. It's whether the system can function in the real-world environments where mines persist—overgrown fields, rocky slopes, and areas with limited infrastructure."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/demining-drones-show-promise-but-battery-life-is-a/subtitle.jpg","alt":"From a lab to a field","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"From a lab to a field"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["The hardware limits are immediate. Drone battery life, payload capacity for advanced sensors, and operation in high winds or rain are non-negotiable constraints. A system that works for two hours in a temperate climate is useless for a full day's work in varied terrain. Scale-up friction involves more than cost; it includes certification of autonomous systems in life-or-death scenarios and the reliability of AI against countless ground clutter types, from discarded metal to peculiar rocks. Genuine use cases exist for large-area assessment, but the marketing filter requires us to state that AI currently suggests, not confirms, a threat. Final verification and removal remain intensely manual, human-led processes.\nThe community is responding with cautious optimism, focusing on incremental integration rather than full autonomy. Research from institutions like ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://rpg.ifi.uzh.ch/","children":"ETH Zurich's Robotics and Perception Group"}]," shows progress, but deployment reality means pairing new tech with proven, slower methods."]}]]}]
